Hmm, sure, cryptography in better supported compared to pycrypto. But has its own share of problems, e.g. its dependency on openssl, which results in availability of certain algorithms for certain openssl versions only and updating openssl from 1.0.2 to 1.1.0 on a linux system is a perfect recipe for disaster for that matter...

OTOH, pycrypto is fully self contained. With [PyCryptodome](https://github.com/Legrandin/pycryptodome), there's a decent well formed and supported successor of this unmaintained package.

@aikchar If you're looking for an encrypted file backend, you may want to check out [keyrings.cryptfile](https://github.com/frispete/keyrings.cryptfile), which is a cryptographically advanced alternative to the encryped file backends of this project. For the reasons given above, it is using PyCryptodome for encryption (all available authenticated symmetric AES modes) and argon2_cffi as KDF.

